00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:03.160
All right. Hello. So I'm here to talk about the Innovative Molecular Analysis

81
00:05:03.260 --> 00:05:07.180
Technologies program, or IMAT. So the mission

82
00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:11.160
of the IMAT program is to catalyze multidisciplinary development of new

83
00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:14.700
technologies that will allow us to grapple with the complexity of cancer

84
00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:18.380
biology and create new possibilities in the fight against

85
00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:22.340
cancer. And IMAT supports a diverse array of technology types,

86
00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:26.420
from new sequencing technologies, proteomics methods,

87
00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:30.860
biomarker detection assays, biospecimen science tools,

88
00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:35.340
imaging tools or microscopy platforms, new ways to model cancer,

89
00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.980
synthetic biology systems, immuno-oncology approaches.

90
00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:43.480
There are a couple of very specific technology types that are out of

91
00:05:43.580 --> 00:05:47.240
scope for IMAT, because they're being supported elsewhere, such as

92
00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:50.720
informatics tools, and we're going to hear about the ITCR program soon.

93
00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.500
But IMAT is really interested in supporting the development of new

94
00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:59.500
technical capabilities that would be broadly useful for cancer

95
00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:03.404
researchSo here we have the technology development pipeline,

96
00:06:03.464 --> 00:06:07.174
where we start with kind of a raw concept or idea that goes all the way through

97
00:06:07.184 --> 00:06:10.004
dissemination of a new working technology.

98
00:06:10.024 --> 00:06:13.324
And we support technology development in this program with two mechanisms, the

99
00:06:13.424 --> 00:06:17.063
R61 for very early stage, proof of concept

100
00:06:17.304 --> 00:06:20.364
projects, and the R33 for more advanced development.

101
00:06:21.084 --> 00:06:24.694
And you don't need to get the R61 to then compete for the R33.

102
00:06:25.144 --> 00:06:29.064
You can come into this program and apply for whichever mechanism

103
00:06:29.544 --> 00:06:32.324
best suits your stage in technology development.

104
00:06:33.184 --> 00:06:36.704
So the R61, this early-stage mechanism, has a budget limit of

105
00:06:36.714 --> 00:06:40.164
$150,000 direct costs per year for up to three years.

106
00:06:40.664 --> 00:06:44.434
Again, these are for the technical proof of principle experiments.

107
00:06:44.504 --> 00:06:48.384
There's a very high bar for innovation, and we consider this a high-risk,

108
00:06:48.824 --> 00:06:49.884
high-reward program.

109
00:06:50.924 --> 00:06:54.724
Similar to an R21, a mechanism you might be more familiar with, there's no

110
00:06:54.824 --> 00:06:58.534
preliminary data required for the R61, although it's accepted if

111
00:06:58.584 --> 00:07:02.044
available. And there should really be a question of feasibility, right?

112
00:07:02.124 --> 00:07:05.004
This is a high-risk, high-reward mechanism.

113
00:07:05.484 --> 00:07:09.404
If you have a low-risk, high-reward project, there's probably a

114
00:07:09.444 --> 00:07:12.944
different mechanism that's better suited for you, or you could compete for a

115
00:07:12.984 --> 00:07:16.904
standard R01 or R21 that goes to a standing study

116
00:07:16.944 --> 00:07:20.934
section. But this program is really built to support things that are not

117
00:07:20.944 --> 00:07:23.364
being supported in other mechanisms.

118
00:07:23.964 --> 00:07:27.804
The R33 is for more advanced development with a budget limit of $300,000 a year for

119
00:07:27.844 --> 00:07:31.363
up to three years for improvements, optimizations, technical

120
00:07:31.444 --> 00:07:35.384
validation of methods that have the preliminary data to demonstrate

121
00:07:35.404 --> 00:07:39.364
feasibility and need further improvements to be ready for broad

122
00:07:39.424 --> 00:07:43.354
adoption. And so those considerations for broad adoption start to come

123
00:07:43.384 --> 00:07:45.204
into play for this R33 phase.

124
00:07:46.584 --> 00:07:50.114
Some tips for building a strong application is to start by

125
00:07:50.164 --> 00:07:53.364
identifying a critical gap in currently available methods.

126
00:07:53.784 --> 00:07:57.424
We can't do this type of research because the technology doesn't

127
00:07:57.484 --> 00:08:01.424
exist. And then describe how your proposed technology is

128
00:08:01.464 --> 00:08:05.364
going to fill that gap. Because this is a high-risk, high-reward program,

129
00:08:05.424 --> 00:08:09.223
there are always questions is, why has no one done this before?

130
00:08:09.344 --> 00:08:13.224
How are you going to succeed here when others have failed to build this

131
00:08:13.233 --> 00:08:17.154
kind of technology? Are there breakthroughs in tangentially related fields

132
00:08:17.204 --> 00:08:19.884
that now make this sort of thing possible?

133
00:08:19.924 --> 00:08:23.824
Do you have a specific expertise that makes you have a unique

134
00:08:23.834 --> 00:08:27.074
perspective that allows you to approach this problem in a different way?

135
00:08:28.304 --> 00:08:31.434
And does the potential impact justify the risk? Right?

136
00:08:31.464 --> 00:08:34.924
This is high risk, high reward. You need to show us what is that

137
00:08:34.944 --> 00:08:37.664
reward that makes us want to take this risk.

138
00:08:37.684 --> 00:08:39.444
And have you mitigated those risks?

139
00:08:39.453 --> 00:08:42.784
So we do have a risk tolerance in this program, but we want to know that you're

140
00:08:42.824 --> 00:08:46.793
going into the project with your eyes open, that you know where the risks are, and

141
00:08:46.824 --> 00:08:48.924
you're prepared to address any of those challenges.

142
00:08:51.644 --> 00:08:54.544
Another question is: Do you understand the needs of the end users?

143
00:08:55.004 --> 00:08:58.484
Developing a new technology that has better capabilities than what currently

144
00:08:58.524 --> 00:09:02.293
exists isn't going to be impactful unless someone is really

145
00:09:02.324 --> 00:09:06.084
wanting those capabilities. It's not just building something better, but are you

146
00:09:06.104 --> 00:09:07.374
building something useful?

147
00:09:09.244 --> 00:09:13.124
And thinking about broader adoption, particularly if you're in that R33 phase,

148
00:09:13.604 --> 00:09:17.504
would others be interested in using this method, and would others be able

149
00:09:17.824 --> 00:09:20.724
to use this method? Have you considered the existing

150
00:09:20.784 --> 00:09:24.004
infrastructure of the lab that might be your end user?

151
00:09:24.414 --> 00:09:28.144
Do you understand the workflow that this new technology might be integrated into,

152
00:09:28.664 --> 00:09:32.263
and the types of data that they have the infrastructure to analyze?

153
00:09:34.684 --> 00:09:38.404
And last, technologies can be used in lots of different ways.

154
00:09:38.424 --> 00:09:41.724
But in this application, you should really focus on the most

155
00:09:41.764 --> 00:09:45.304
impactful cancer-relevant use case for your

156
00:09:45.344 --> 00:09:46.524
validation experiments.

157
00:09:49.304 --> 00:09:52.444
The IMAP program also requires that all applications include

158
00:09:52.724 --> 00:09:54.504
quantitative performance measures.

159
00:09:54.513 --> 00:09:58.314
This is the target of performance that you hope to achieve over the course of your

160
00:09:58.364 --> 00:10:02.293
aims. It's very specific to the exact technology that you're proposing, but

161
00:10:02.324 --> 00:10:06.293
it could be any quantitative metric: sensitivity, specificity, resolution,

162
00:10:06.444 --> 00:10:10.064
yield, throughput, cost. And it needs to include the numerical target,

163
00:10:10.484 --> 00:10:14.464
not just that you're proposing a new technology that will be faster, but putting

164
00:10:14.524 --> 00:10:18.444
in that number. "I'm going to reduce assay time from X days to Y hours."

165
00:10:19.304 --> 00:10:22.344
This is a great place to address any potential risks.

166
00:10:22.384 --> 00:10:25.224
So if the reviewers might be concerned that you're going to have a really high

167
00:10:25.284 --> 00:10:29.184
false negative rate, then you're going to propose to test the false

168
00:10:29.264 --> 00:10:33.204
negative rate and set some sort of go, no-go criteria that you're not

169
00:10:33.254 --> 00:10:36.444
going to move on until you've gotten that rate below a certain number

170
00:10:37.044 --> 00:10:40.284
because that's what number would make this technology useful.

171
00:10:41.624 --> 00:10:45.604
And it's really important to put these performance measures in the context

172
00:10:45.644 --> 00:10:49.374
of the existing technologies. So having some sort of table where you have

173
00:10:49.464 --> 00:10:53.064
your technology versus the gold standard or other currently available

174
00:10:53.104 --> 00:10:57.084
technologies. And your technology doesn't have to be superior to

175
00:10:57.124 --> 00:11:01.024
what's currently available in every single way, but you need to identify the

176
00:11:01.064 --> 00:11:04.564
certain areas where it will outperform the competitors and then

177
00:11:04.604 --> 00:11:06.324
justify why that's important.

178
00:11:08.284 --> 00:11:11.984
All of these applications are reviewed by special emphasis panels, so those

179
00:11:12.024 --> 00:11:14.884
panels are really focused on these technology development grants.

180
00:11:15.584 --> 00:11:18.804
And there are a couple of things that I hear a lot in these panels that can sort of

181
00:11:18.904 --> 00:11:21.804
kill an otherwise promising application.

182
00:11:21.844 --> 00:11:25.344
The first is they might say, "This is a cool idea, super creative, super

183
00:11:25.444 --> 00:11:29.324
innovative, but I just don't see why we need this in cancer research

184
00:11:29.604 --> 00:11:33.504
specifically." So technologies can be broadly enabling, but

185
00:11:33.544 --> 00:11:37.524
this is an NCI opportunity, so you really need to tie it back to a

186
00:11:37.604 --> 00:11:40.044
challenge or a problem in cancer research.

187
00:11:41.464 --> 00:11:43.984
The proposed aims don't match the gap they've identified.

188
00:11:44.444 --> 00:11:48.364
So if you think that there's a challenge in clinical diagnostics

189
00:11:48.524 --> 00:11:52.324
and you're going to solve that challenge, but all of your experiments are

190
00:11:52.364 --> 00:11:55.944
designed around use in a basic research lab, there's kind of this

191
00:11:56.164 --> 00:12:00.064
disconnect. And maybe use in a basic research lab is a steppingstone

192
00:12:00.124 --> 00:12:03.824
to the ultimate goal of being more clinically relevant, but then you need to

193
00:12:03.844 --> 00:12:07.684
argue that. That in this application, we're going to show proof of concept in

194
00:12:07.724 --> 00:12:11.224
this setting, and here is my plan to get it to

195
00:12:11.304 --> 00:12:13.084
addressing this gap that I've identified.

196
00:12:14.356 --> 00:12:17.936
They say the tool will be impactful for this reason, but they don't include

197
00:12:17.976 --> 00:12:21.316
performance measures for that. If you're saying that currently available

198
00:12:21.326 --> 00:12:24.506
technologies are not fast enough, and we need a faster technology,

199
00:12:25.276 --> 00:12:28.876
are you going to measure how fast this is in order to show to the

200
00:12:28.896 --> 00:12:32.836
reviewers, "Look how impactful this will be, that I'm going to reduce

201
00:12:33.036 --> 00:12:36.106
assay time by this amount, and that will be useful for this

202
00:12:36.136 --> 00:12:40.116
reason." They haven't acknowledged other efforts in the area

203
00:12:40.136 --> 00:12:42.006
or compared it to alternative technologies.

204
00:12:42.606 --> 00:12:45.976
It's really important to put those performance measures in the context of what's

205
00:12:46.036 --> 00:12:49.556
currently available, but also think about those performance measures are your

206
00:12:49.616 --> 00:12:52.246
target of performance three years from now.

207
00:12:52.736 --> 00:12:56.626
So are there other people that are also trying to do something in this area, and

208
00:12:56.696 --> 00:13:00.376
how is your technology going to compete in three years from

209
00:13:00.416 --> 00:13:04.066
now? And you can't always predict that, but knowing what's going

210
00:13:04.136 --> 00:13:07.966
on and saying, "I think they may fail for these reasons, and

211
00:13:08.056 --> 00:13:11.596
I'm going to succeed because I have this approach," or saying, "Their

212
00:13:11.636 --> 00:13:15.256
technology will be useful for this use case, but I'm building mine

213
00:13:15.516 --> 00:13:19.256
very specifically for this application." And just acknowledging that you

214
00:13:19.416 --> 00:13:21.216
know what's going on in the field.

215
00:13:22.516 --> 00:13:25.776
And last, the most innovative part has already been done.

216
00:13:26.316 --> 00:13:27.836
What they propose now is incremental.

217
00:13:28.316 --> 00:13:30.496
I especially see this a lot when there's a mismatch.

218
00:13:30.646 --> 00:13:34.176
Somebody applied to the R61 when they really should have applied for the

219
00:13:34.296 --> 00:13:38.206
R33. Because that R61 mechanism has a very high bar for

220
00:13:38.236 --> 00:13:41.836
innovation, and if somebody uses the word incremental when

221
00:13:41.876 --> 00:13:44.556
describing your project, it can be a real killer.

